{"text": "2mi(pi\u0000eiA(xi))2+eiV(xi) (50.11)\n\nThis Hamiltonian assumes the presence of AwhileVis potential which is created by all the other particles. Once we\n\nconsider the many body system, the potential Vis replaced by a mutual Coulomb interaction term, from which the\n\nforces on any of the particles are derived:\n\nH=X\n\ni1\n\n2mi(pi\u0000eiA(xi))2+1\n\n2X\n\ni;jeiej\n\njxi\u0000xjj(50.12)\n\n249\n\nBy itself the direct Coulomb interaction between the particles seems to contradict relativity. This is due to the non-\n\ninvariant way that we had separated the electric\n\neld into components. In fact our treatment is exact: as a whole the\n\nHamiltonian that we got is Lorentz invariant, as far as the EM\n\neld is concerned.\n\nThe factor 1 =2 in the Coulomb interaction is there in order to compensate for the double counting of the interactions.\n\nWhat about the diagonal terms i=j? We can keep them if we want because they add just a\n\nnite constant term\n\nto the Hamiltonian. The \"self interaction\" in\n\nnite term can be regularized by assuming that each particle has a very\n\nsmall radius. To drop this constant from the Hamiltonian means that \"in\n\nnite distance\" between the particles is taken\n\nas the reference state for the energy. However, it is more convenient to keep this in\n\nnite constant in the Hamiltonian,\n\nbecause then we can write:\n\nH=X\n\ni1\n\n2mi(pi\u0000eiA(xi))2+1\n\n8\u0019Z\n\nE2\n\nqd3x (50.13)\n\nIn order to get the latter expression we have used the following identity:\n\n1\n\n2Z\u001a(x)\u001a(x0)\n\njx\u0000x0jd3xd3x0=1\n\n8\u0019Z\n\nE2\n\nqd3x (50.14)\n\nThe derivation of this identity is based on Gauss law, integration by parts, and using the fact that the Laplacian of\n\n1=jx\u0000x0jis a delta function.", "embedding": [0.017613644, 0.031081429, 0.032383114, 0.008321446, -0.030411506, 0.01157457, 0.0074777594, -0.0033520286, -0.028649895, 0.050493896, 0.009253645, 0.018827463, -0.009514841, -0.065123536, -0.03183619